n Bhaird</b> ‘son of the poet’. The surname occurs throughout Ireland, where three different branches of the family are known as professional poets."],"variants":[{"name":"Warshawsky","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Ari, Hyman.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from the city of Warsaw (Polish <i>Warszawa</i>), which became the capital of Poland at the end of the 16th century, after the destruction of Kraków by fire.","Americanized form of Polish <b>Warszawski</b>, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Wardman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>wardman</i>, either in the general sense ‘watchman, guard’ (compare   Ward  ) or in the administrative sense ‘representative of a ward within a borough’."]},{"name":"Warde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Donal.","Irish: variant of   Ward  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":8,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Ward was born in 1447, in Badingham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Unknown Ward. She married John E. Derehaugh in 1469, in Badingham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1498, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 51, and was buried in Badingham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1447–1498":"1447–1498","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1473–1524":"1473–1524","–Male":"Surnud","1447":"1447","1469":"1469","1524":"1524","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","20 April 1473":"20. aprill 1473","1496":"1496","1473":"1473","June 1496":"juuni 1496","Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Badingham, Suffolk Coastal District, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1447–1498":"1447–1498","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1473–1524":"1473–1524","–Male":"Kuollut","1447":"1447","1469":"1469","1524":"1524","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","20 April 1473":"20. huhtikuuta 1473","1496":"1496","1473":"1473","June 1496":"kesäkuu 1496","Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Badi